GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 1204
Short Title: Require Seat Belts on School Buses. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Greenfield, Willis, and Logan (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Appropriations, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
May 5, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REQUIRE SEAT BELTS AT ALL DESIGNATED SEATING POSITIONS ON
3 SCHOOL BUSES AND ACTIVITY BUSES PURCHASED, LEASED, OR RENTED BY
4 PUBLIC SCHOOL UNITS AND PRIVATE SCHOOLS.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 115C-240(c) reads as rewritten:
7 "(c) The State Board of Education shall from time to time adopt such rules and regulations
8 with reference to the construction, equipment, color, and maintenance of school buses, the
9 number of pupils who may be permitted to ride at the same time upon any bus, and the age and
10 qualifications of drivers of school buses as it shall deem to be desirable for the purpose of
11 promoting safety in the operation of school buses. Every school bus that is capable of operating
12 on diesel fuel shall be capable of operating on diesel fuel with a minimum biodiesel concentration
13 of B-20, as defined in G.S. 143-58.4. No school bus shall be operated for the transportation of
14 pupils unless such bus is constructed and maintained as prescribed in such regulations and is
15 equipped with adequate heating facilities, a standard signaling device for giving due notice that
16 the bus is about to make a turn, an alternating flashing stoplight on the front of the bus, an
17 alternating flashing stoplight on the rear of the bus, and such other warning devices, fire
18 protective equipment and first aid supplies as may be prescribed for installation upon such buses
19 by the regulation of the State Board of Education.The State Board shall adopt rules that address
20 the construction, equipment, color, and maintenance of school buses, the number of pupils who
21 may be permitted to ride at the same time upon any bus, and the age and qualifications of drivers
22 of school buses. Every school bus operated for the transportation of pupils shall comply with the
23 rules adopted by the State Board. At a minimum, those rules shall address all of the following:
24 (1) Diesel engine requirements. – Every school bus that is capable of operating
25 on diesel fuel shall be capable of operating on diesel fuel with a minimum
26 biodiesel concentration of B-20, as defined in G.S. 143-58.4.
27 (2) Equipment requirements. – Every school bus shall be equipped with the
28 following:
29 a. Adequate heating facilities.
30 b. A standard signaling device for giving notice that the bus is about to
31 make a turn.
32 c. An alternating flashing stoplight on the rear of the bus.
33 d. Type-two seat belt assemblies that are compliant with all applicable
34 regulations adopted under 49 U.S.C. § 30111 at all designated seating
35 positions, except the State Board may adopt reasonable rules
*H1204-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 modifying this requirement with respect to integrated child safety
2 restraint systems, the transportation of students with disabilities, and
3 the use of other federally approved restraint or securement systems
4 where required by federal law.
5 e. Other warning devices, fire protective equipment, and first aid
6 supplies deemed necessary by the State Board."
7 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 115C-247 reads as rewritten:
8 "§ 115C-247. Purchase of activity buses by local boards.
9 The several local boards of education in the State are hereby authorized and empowered to
10 take title to school buses purchased with local or community funds for the purpose of transporting
11 pupils to and from athletic events and for other local school activity purposes, and commonly
12 referred to as activity buses.
13 Each local board of education that operates activity buses shall adopt a policy relative to the
14 proper use of the vehicles. The policy shall permit the use of these buses for travel to athletic
15 events during the regular season and playoffs and for travel to other school-sponsored activities.
16 The provisions of G.S. 115C-42 shall be fully applicable to the ownership and operation of
17 such activity school buses. Activity buses may also be used as provided in G.S. 115C-243.
18 A local board of education shall only purchase, lease, or rent activity buses equipped with
19 type-two seat belt assemblies that are compliant with all applicable regulations adopted under 49
20 U.S.C. § 30111 at all designated seating positions, except the local board of education may adopt
21 reasonable policies modifying this requirement with respect to integrated child safety restraint
22 systems, the transportation of students with disabilities, and the use of other federally approved
23 restraint or securement systems where required by federal law."
24 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 115C-218.40 reads as rewritten:
25 "§ 115C-218.40. Charter school transportation.
26 The charter school may provide transportation for students enrolled at the school. The charter
27 school shall develop a transportation plan so that transportation is not a barrier to any student
28 who resides in the local school administrative unit in which the school is located. The charter
29 school is not required to provide transportation to any student who lives within one and one-half
30 miles of the school. At the request of the charter school and if the local board of the local school
31 administrative unit in which the charter school is located operates a school bus system, then that
32 local board may contract with the charter school to provide transportation in accordance with the
33 charter school's transportation plan to students who reside in the local school administrative unit
34 and who reside at least one and one-half miles of the charter school. A local board may charge
35 the charter school a reasonable charge that is sufficient to cover the cost of providing this
36 transportation. Furthermore, a local board may refuse to provide transportation under this section
37 if it demonstrates there is no available space on buses it intends to operate during the term of the
38 contract or it would not be practically feasible to provide this transportation. If a charter school
39 purchases, leases, or rents any school bus or activity bus for the purpose of providing
40 transportation for students, the charter school shall purchase, lease, or rent vehicles equipped
41 with type-two seat belt assemblies that are compliant with all applicable regulations adopted
42 under 49 U.S.C. § 30111 at all designated seating positions, except the charter school may adopt
43 reasonable policies modifying this requirement with respect to integrated child safety restraint
44 systems, the transportation of students with disabilities, and the use of other federally approved
45 restraint or securement systems where required by federal law."
46 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 115C-238.66 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
47 "(23) School transportation. – If a regional school purchases, leases, or rents any
48 school bus or activity bus for the purpose of providing transportation for
49 students, the regional school shall purchase, lease, or rent vehicles equipped
50 with type-two seat belt assemblies that are compliant with all applicable
51 regulations adopted under 49 U.S.C. § 30111 at all designated seating
